05223nam a22007455i 9780857450722DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574507227 a10.1515/97808574507222doi  a(DE-B1597)636942  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aN8725b.S738 2008 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a700.1/0304aThe State and the Arts :bArticulating Power and Subversion /ced. by Judith Kapferer. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (182 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Architectonics of State Power—Complicity and Resistance -- tChapter 1 The End of Arrogance, the Advent of Persuasion: Public Art in a Multicultural Society -- tChapter 2 Contesting Authenticity and the Promethean Complex: The Cultural Politics of Globalization -- tChapter 3 Hijacking Cultural Policies: Art as a Healthy Virus within Social Strategies of Resistance -- tChapter 4 Engaging with History by Performing Tradition: The Poetic Politics of Indigenous Australian Festivals -- tChapter 5 Urban Design and State Power: City Spaces and the Public Sphere -- tChapter 6 Self and the City: The Politics of Monuments -- tChapter 7 The Culture Industries: Symbolic Economies and Critical Practices -- tChapter 8 The Arts, the Stat e, and the EU: Cultural Policy in the Making of Europe -- tChapter 9 Political Art, Cultural Policy, and Artistic Agency -- tChapter 10 The Feeling for Gray: Aesthetics, Politics, and Shifting German Regimes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJudith Kapferer and her collaborators present an insightful volume that interrogates relations between the state and the arts in diverse national and cultural settings. The authors critique the taken-for-granted assumption about the place of the arts in liberal or social democratic states and the role of the arts in supporting or opposing the ideological work of government and non-government institutions. This innovative volume explores the challenges posed by the state to the arts and by the arts to the state, focusing on several transformations of the interrelations between state and commercial arts policies in the current era. These ongoing challenges include the control of repressive tolerance, complicity with and resistance to state power, and the commoditization of the arts, including their accommodation to market and state apparatuses. While endeavouring to avoid the currently dominant pragmatic and didactic priorities of officialdom, the contributors tackle social and cultural policy and practice in the arts as well as connections between national states and dissenting art from a range of genres.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aArt and state. 0aArtsxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aBeunders, Henri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChong, Terence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFokidis, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenry, Rosita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKipphoff, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiles, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSassatelli, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValentine, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct